{"summary":"Both amendments describe real persistence-integrity defects. The completion-journal format is not safely round-trippable for all currently valid identifiers, and the lineage append API still allows writing incomplete task-run rows to disk.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-10-a35fc4da","decision":"accept","rationale":"`render_completion_journal_details` encodes structured fields with a raw `\", \"` delimiter, while `CompletionJournalDetails::parse` relies on that delimiter to recover `project_id`, `run_id`, and `plan_hash`. The only guard is `debug_assert!`, which is absent in release builds, and the current identifier constructors still allow values containing that delimiter. That makes the render/parse pair non-reversible for legal inputs, so `repairable_completion_event` can fail to merge replayed completion events and `append_event_if_missing` will append duplicates instead of performing the intended idempotent repair."},{"amendment_id":"fr-10-9fd118d3","decision":"accept","rationale":"`append_task_run` writes the supplied `TaskRunEntry` verbatim even though it is also given the authoritative `milestone_id` separately. Because `milestone_id` remains optional on the entry and the existing backfill happens only after deserialization in `read_task_runs_from_path`, a caller can still create fresh on-disk rows with no embedded `milestone_id`. That leaves persisted lineage data incomplete and undermines the stated self-contained-entry invariant until some later rewrite happens to repair it."}]}